ble to complete its task. Looking at the session history, this cron is actually still running with the last update from 11:29 AM showing it was waiting on tool calls, so it's not stuck—I just misidentified it earlier. The real issue was a different cron job that got cleared and resolved. The old `cron:e7885813` status from the heartbeat file is stale — the QLHV group session is actually still running, and `cron:e7885813` has been cleaned up by the system even though the heartbeat state hasn't caught up yet. Looking at the session timestamps more carefully, `cron:e7885813` actually shows an update at 11:46, which is after the heartbeat was recorded, so the heartbeat data is stale and doesn't reflect the current state. I'm realizing the cron state file might be outdated—the heartbeat recorded it as running, but the actual session history shows it was last updated around 11:46 with a message about timing out, and the \"sessions_send timed out\" thinking suggests it actually completed its task and stopped, so the cron itself should have ended as well. The cron jobs all completed successfully with the delivery issue resolved, and the two other cron sessions are still running normally. The overall pipeline is healthy with no active blockers, so this is just a routine status update—nothing has actually broken. I'm verifying the changes against what's actually changed in the heartbeat state. The cron sessions have shifted status or been cleaned up, the main session is done, and there's a new cron session running, but the core pipeline health and blocker status remain the same. I've identified the key changes: the cron:e7885813 session cleared after the delivery attempt ended around 11:46 AM, and both of its sibling cron sessions are now finished. The new cron:ed2d0b5d is running as expected, and the pipeline remains healthy with no blockers, so this is just a routine status update that I can send quietly.","thinkingSignature":"7eb8c48efb592508f733b5a66280d5c1d0ba5678ce6d3bf